WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.000
 Hello everybody and welcome to another walkthrough and this time we're going to do some walkthrough in the CDC 6504 machine language emulator.

00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:14.600
 So let's first just talk a little bit about all the things that we can do here.

00:00:14.600 --> 00:00:17.640
 So this is kind of our machine language emulator.

00:00:17.640 --> 00:00:19.280
 We have a series of instructions.

00:00:19.280 --> 00:00:20.520
 It starts out all zeros.

00:00:20.520 --> 00:00:21.480
 We have data memory.

00:00:21.480 --> 00:00:23.120
 We have 256 instructions.

00:00:23.120 --> 00:00:24.920
 We have 256 data memories.

00:00:24.920 --> 00:00:30.280
 We have an accumulator register, an X register, and a Y register taken from the 6502.

00:00:30.280 --> 00:00:33.480
 And then we have the program counter, which points to where we're at.

00:00:33.480 --> 00:00:37.000
 Our program counter currently says zero, pointing at instruction memory zero.

00:00:37.000 --> 00:00:45.200
 The Z is a flag that once we do a calculation or store some stuff and the result of that is a zero, the Z will check and N stands for negative.

00:00:45.200 --> 00:00:48.320
 We can branch if negative, branch if positive, branch of zero.

00:00:48.320 --> 00:00:52.320
 And so these are used to do a pattern of compare, then branch.

00:00:52.320 --> 00:00:55.680
 We can load a program from here.

00:00:55.680 --> 00:00:58.520
 Let's just load a simple sample so you can see it.

00:00:58.520 --> 00:01:01.280
 You can also view the assembly language.

00:01:01.280 --> 00:01:05.960
 And so what I'll tend to do is I'll tend to put the assembly language over here.

00:01:05.960 --> 00:01:08.800
 And I've got this narrate execution.

00:01:08.800 --> 00:01:19.440
 You can hover over each of the memory locations and it tells you, for example, that this 0x00 location is a E2 in hex and it is a clear instruction.

00:01:19.440 --> 00:01:23.360
 Now, sometimes this is instruction and sometimes it's data when we're doing load immediates.

00:01:23.360 --> 00:01:27.040
 It tells you, you know, if it's ASCII, it'll tell you what the ASCII character is.

00:01:27.040 --> 00:01:28.400
 And so it has to interpret this.

00:01:28.400 --> 00:01:32.960
 But this is just zeros and ones in the computer memory and it's contextualized what's going on.

00:01:32.960 --> 00:01:37.600
 So this is just a clear instruction, an increment instruction and an increment instruction.

00:01:37.600 --> 00:01:40.800
 And then a break, which is just a zero, which stops the thing from running.

00:01:40.800 --> 00:01:44.200
 And we can see the same thing right here in the assemblies.

00:01:44.200 --> 00:01:46.560
 Clear, increment, increment, break.

00:01:46.560 --> 00:01:49.680
 Eventually, we're going to want to just look at the assembly.

00:01:49.680 --> 00:01:53.720
 It just makes our lives a lot simpler to watch what's going on.

00:01:53.720 --> 00:01:55.840
 But reality, it's zeros and ones.

00:01:55.840 --> 00:01:58.880
 And so we have a couple of options here.

00:01:58.880 --> 00:02:00.880
 We can start the application.

00:02:00.880 --> 00:02:02.320
 We can run it a single step.

00:02:02.320 --> 00:02:05.920
 We can reset it, but that clears everything and we've got to load a new program.

00:02:05.920 --> 00:02:12.040
 But we have this cool feature called narrate execution, and it slows it down and describes everything that's going on.

00:02:12.040 --> 00:02:14.360
 And so I'm going to tell you in advance what's going to happen.

00:02:14.360 --> 00:02:17.920
 It's going to clear the X register and you've got to watch the X register here.

00:02:17.920 --> 00:02:23.640
 And it's going to add one to the X register, watch the X register, and then add one again to the X register.

00:02:23.640 --> 00:02:29.360
 And when it's all said and done, it'll stop and nothing else will have changed except the X register will have a two in it.

00:02:29.360 --> 00:02:39.720
 So I'm going to move this over here and you can kind of watch as the program counter moves along and just kind of that assembly is there for you to remember.

00:02:39.720 --> 00:02:42.440
 Later, you can write assembly and get it assembled.

00:02:42.440 --> 00:02:46.600
 So let me go ahead, it's got narrate execution turned on and let me start it.

00:02:46.600 --> 00:03:04.240
 PC zero X zero zero clear X register PC zero X zero one increment X register PC zero X zero two increment X register PC zero X zero three break no printed output.

00:03:04.240 --> 00:03:06.760
 OK, so you saw what happened there.

00:03:06.760 --> 00:03:10.040
 Let me go and do this a little more slowly.

00:03:10.040 --> 00:03:13.080
 Let me reload it, load simple sample.

00:03:13.080 --> 00:03:17.200
 And I'm going to instead when we narrate execution, I'm going to hit step.

00:03:17.200 --> 00:03:19.160
 So you saw it run automatically.

00:03:19.160 --> 00:03:20.600
 And so I'm going to do step.

00:03:20.600 --> 00:03:28.040
 It's going to run one instruction and narrate it when I press step PC zero X zero zero clear X register.

00:03:28.040 --> 00:03:31.600
 OK, so notice that the Z flag, it's a one byte instruction.

00:03:31.600 --> 00:03:33.200
 So the PC went up by one.

00:03:33.200 --> 00:03:34.920
 The Z flag is now set.

00:03:34.920 --> 00:03:38.880
 It's not a negative number because the X register is a zero, which is not negative.

00:03:38.880 --> 00:03:42.520
 And that is the result of that particular instruction.

00:03:42.520 --> 00:03:49.160
 So let's step again PC zero X zero one increment X register.

00:03:49.160 --> 00:03:50.680
 So we incremented X.

00:03:50.680 --> 00:03:53.240
 So if we look at X, X is now gone from zero to one.

00:03:53.240 --> 00:03:56.000
 The program counters ready for the next instruction.

00:03:56.000 --> 00:04:00.480
 But because X is now one, neither the Z nor the N flag is set.

00:04:00.480 --> 00:04:07.040
 So let's step one more time PC zero X zero two increment X register.

00:04:07.040 --> 00:04:12.440
 OK, so now the next instruction is going to be zero X zero three and the X register is two.

00:04:12.440 --> 00:04:14.720
 The Z and the N flags are set accordingly.

00:04:14.720 --> 00:04:18.760
 When we step again, we're going to hit this break, which is a stop.

00:04:18.760 --> 00:04:24.160
 And then the program executions zero X zero three break no printed output.

00:04:24.160 --> 00:04:27.680
 And what it's talking about no printed output is in future ones.

00:04:27.680 --> 00:04:30.000
 We put some data when we put data in here.

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:34.440
 The printed output comes out of the first few up to a zero byte in the memory.

00:04:34.440 --> 00:04:37.160
 But this one has no particular memory.

00:04:37.160 --> 00:04:41.560
 OK, so let's just take a look at a couple of other things that we have.

00:04:41.560 --> 00:04:43.520
 It has a bunch of documentation.

00:04:43.520 --> 00:04:44.800
 It's pretty cool.

00:04:44.800 --> 00:04:47.800
 It's probably more you can read this.

00:04:47.800 --> 00:04:49.040
 I can read this.

00:04:49.040 --> 00:04:49.760
 It's pretty cool.

00:04:49.760 --> 00:04:53.080
 That's just a URL that you can go paste into AI if you want.

00:04:53.080 --> 00:04:55.360
 And you can ask AI for help writing this code.

00:04:55.360 --> 00:04:57.360
 And we'll see how well AI does with this.

00:04:57.360 --> 00:04:58.640
 But it has documentation.

00:04:58.640 --> 00:05:01.080
 We also need an ASCII chart, right?

00:05:01.080 --> 00:05:02.280
 This is not a text one.

00:05:02.280 --> 00:05:04.240
 So but we have a little ASCII chart.

00:05:04.240 --> 00:05:06.920
 That tells it the space is 32 decimal.

00:05:06.920 --> 00:05:10.240
 It's 20 hex and zero zero one zero zero.

00:05:10.240 --> 00:05:16.840
 And remember that hex you can do a four bit to one column hex to binary conversion.

00:05:16.840 --> 00:05:20.240
 And for me, I start seeing things like I'll look at like this one here.

00:05:20.240 --> 00:05:21.280
 I know that's a seven.

00:05:21.280 --> 00:05:22.440
 So that's twenty seven.

00:05:22.440 --> 00:05:26.080
 I'll see this one one one and I'll see that as an F.

00:05:26.080 --> 00:05:31.160
 So you'll start to see hopefully after a while, you'll kind of have a hex to binary conversion in your mind.

00:05:31.160 --> 00:05:32.760
 Decimal is a pain in the neck.

00:05:32.760 --> 00:05:35.800
 I just got a hand convert both decimal to hex and binary.

00:05:35.800 --> 00:05:40.720
 And so that's pretty much all of the features of the application.

00:05:40.720 --> 00:05:45.800
 And so next, we're going to go through some of these things in a little bit more detail.

00:05:45.800 --> 00:05:47.600
 And so come to those in a bit.

